From 1956, the PTA brought a significant contribution to the crowned development of success of the meteorological rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), that became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was finished in 1957 and the first launch took place October 10 1958.
This rocket of a reach of 1800 meters had a length of 80 cm and weighed a little less than 5 kg.
Afterward was constructed an improved version, RM-1A and, during the summer 1959, essays of flight of the rocket to two floors RM-2 were started in the desert of Bledov.
This rocket had a length of 1.4 meters and weighed probably 11.5 kg.
The following prototype should have been able to carry out concrete scientific works - the rocket RM-34 should have had a going reach until 14.5 km and serve to observe the wind in altitude.
But in 1963, all the works of development were stopped.
The rocket Meteor-1 perfect during the period 1962 - 1965, succeeded the first rockets of type RM.
This rocket, conceived with two floors, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they distinguished themselves by the dimensions of the reserved space to the scientific tools.
The rocket Meteor-1A had access to a space offering a volume of 0.4 liters, while in Meteor-1B this volume was of 0.34 liters and in Meteor-1C of 0.62 liters.
The maximum reach of all these types of vehicle was of 37 km.
In the period 1965 - 1968, the rockets Meteor-2 were perfected in the aeronautical institute, the first essays of flight began in October 1970.
The rocket Meteor-2 had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to transport a useful load of 10 kg to an about altitude 60 km.
Afterward were constructed the versions Meteor-2H and Meteor-3.
